What is the Kernel?

The kernel is the heart of Linux.
It directly talks to hardware and controls everything.

ğŸ‘‰ Without the kernel, Linux cannot exist.

What the kernel does:

Talks to CPU, RAM, disk, network, devices

Manages processes (which program runs when)

Manages memory (who gets RAM)

Manages filesystems

Handles hardware drivers

Controls system calls (how programs request resources)

Simple example:

When you run:

ls


ls â†’ asks the kernel

Kernel â†’ reads disk

Kernel â†’ returns file list

ğŸ“ Kernel file location:

/boot/vmlinuz-*


ğŸ’¡ Kernel runs in kernel space (very powerful, very protected)

2ï¸âƒ£ Libraries â€” Helpers for Programs ğŸ“š
What are Libraries?

Libraries are pre-written code that programs reuse instead of writing everything again.

ğŸ‘‰ Programs do NOT talk to the kernel directly.
They use libraries.

Why libraries exist:

Avoid rewriting common code

Make programs smaller

Provide standard behavior

Common Linux library:

glibc (GNU C Library)

Example:

A program wants to:

Open a file

Print text

Use network

Instead of writing kernel code, it calls:

printf()
open()
read()


These functions live in libraries, which then talk to the kernel.

ğŸ“ Library locations:

/lib
/lib64
/usr/lib
/usr/lib64


ğŸ’¡ Libraries run in user space

