What are System Utilities?

These are basic command-line tools used to manage the system.

ğŸ‘‰ They are just programs, but very important ones.

Examples:

File tools: ls, cp, mv, rm

Process tools: ps, top, kill

Disk tools: df, mount, umount

Network tools: ip, ping, ss

User tools: useradd, passwd

ğŸ“ Utility locations:

/bin
/sbin
/usr/bin
/usr/sbin

Flow:

User â†’ Utility â†’ Library â†’ Kernel â†’ Hardware

ğŸ’¡ Utilities are the interface between humans and Linux internals.

4ï¸âƒ£ Configuration Files â€” Settings of the System âš™ï¸
What are Configuration Files?

These are text files that control how programs and services behave.

ğŸ‘‰ Linux does NOT use registry like Windows
ğŸ‘‰ Everything is file-based

Key properties:

Plain text

Editable

Read at startup or reload time

Examples:
File	Purpose
/etc/passwd	User accounts
/etc/shadow	Passwords
/etc/ssh/sshd_config	SSH settings
/etc/fstab	Disk mount rules
/etc/hosts	Hostname resolution

ğŸ“ Main location:

/etc

Example:
Port 22
PermitRootLogin no


This config controls SSH behavior.

ğŸ’¡ Change config â†’ restart service â†’ new behavior

